ce. It explores what kind of promise planning offers, how such a promise is made, and what happens to it through time. The authors, all leading anthropologists, examine the time and space, creativity and agency, authority and responsibility, and conflicting desires that plans attempt to control. They show how the many people involved with planning deal with the discrepancies between what is promised and what is done. The comparative essays offer insight into the expected and unexpected outcomes of planning (from visionary utopias to bureaucratic dystopia or something in-between), how the future is envisioned at the outset, and what actual work is done and how it affects people’s lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCity planning. 0aUrbanization. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAbram, Simone, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAbram, Simone, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBaxstrom, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBear, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoholm, Åsa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGledhill, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJames, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLund, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVike, Halvard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeszkalnys, Gisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeszkalnys, Gisa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311099828340uhttp